Source file ⇒ Hockey.Rmd

The Golden Goal- Gordie Howe


For my project, I chose to analyze some data on Professional Hockey teams. I want to find out what Stanley Cup winners have in common, and if there are any trends in the data that might forego the obvious needs for winning the Cup. So I’m going to try a boatload of things :).

First things first, I got this data from Kaggle. The URL can be found here. I went down the page and looked at the different files they had listed. The one that was of interest to me was the Teams.csv. This contained the following data for each team in each year from 1909 to 2011:

  • year: Year (2005-06 listed as “2005”)

  • lgID: League ID

  • tmID: Team ID

  • franchID: Franchise ID

  • confID: Conference ID (see abbrev.csv for details)

  • divID: Division ID (see abbrev.csv for details)

  • rank: Final standing

  • playoff: Playoff result (see abbrev.csv for details)

  • G: Games

  • W: Wins

  • L: Losses

  • T: Ties

  • OTL: Overtime losses

  • Pts: Points

  • SoW: Shootout wins

  • SoL: Shootout losses

  • GF: Goals for

  • GA: Goals against

  • name: Full team name

  • PIM: Penalty minutes

  • BenchMinor: Bench minors (minutes)

  • PPG: Power play goals

  • PPC: Power play chances

  • SHA: Shorthanded goals against

  • PKG: Power play goals against

  • PKC: Penalty kill chances

  • SHF: Shorthanded goals for

As you can see, I needed the abbrev.csv as well. I loaded them both in after I put the csv’s in the working directory with the following commands:

abbrev <- read.csv("abbrev.csv")
teams <- read.csv("Teams.csv")

I want to find out the key tell-tale signs that a team is going to win the cup. Ideally, I’d like to come up with a magical formula for winning the cup (far fetched, I know). I have a few hypotheses I want to test to uncover my magical formula. But first I want to see some things.

More Goals, More Success?

The first thing I want to know is what percentage of history’s highest scoring teams won the cup? You’ve got to score goals to win- how often do the most powerful offensive teams in history win it all?



Let’s find out what teams were the highest scoring teams in history. To do that we will arrange the teams table by Goals For (GF)

lampLighters <- teams %>%
  arrange(desc(GF))
kable(head(lampLighters))

Wow ok. So the Edmonton Oilers from 1981-1985 were pretty dang good. Seems about right though- a quick Google search showed that Wayne Gretzky (arguably hockey’s greatest player), who played for the Oilers during that time, was consistently breaking his own records during the years of 1980-81 through 1985-86. That would definitely help in a Stanley Cup effort. Incredibly though, they only won in ’83 and ’84. Just goes to show there’s no I in Team, and that you need to supplement and support superstar talent. I digress…
So 2/5 for the Oilers is really not that bad- but let’s look at the bigger picture here… of the so-called lampLighters, let’s take the top 25% and see who actually won the cup with all their offensive firepower.

Of the top 25% of the NHL’s highest scoring teams in history, only less than 7% of the time do they go on to win the cup. That’s incredible. How did I get those numbers?
The top 25% is 380 teams. Of those teams, only 26 won the cup (which equals about 6.8%). So a 7% Stanley Cup win percentage isn’t exactly the formula for success I was looking for. Let’s try some other seemingly logical things.

“You’ve got to find a way to win”

Well, other than scoring goals, you’ve got to win games in order to be successful. That doesn’t necessarily mean scoring more goals will help you win, but there are those teams that seem to win no matter how tight the margin. Hockey people like to describe those teams as teams that find ways to win.
So the question here is- what percentage of the NHL’s most winningest teams in history during the regular season go on to win the Stanley Cup?
Let’s find out the most winningest teams in NHL history.

wayfinders <- top15winners %>%

Of the 229 most winningest teams in NHL history, only 34 of them FOUND A WAY to keep winning through the playoffs. So the strategy of winning a ton of games to try and win the cup is coming in at a payoff rate of about 14.8%. That’s double the success rate of just scoring a lot. Improvement!
So we know that winning games is important, and that scoring goals helps win games. What else can help win Lord Stanley’s Cup?

What Makes a Chamionship-Winning Team?

Well, if you’re going to score a lot, you need to make sure your opponents aren’t scoring just as much if not more than you! So let’s minimize the Goals Allowed (GA)! This signifies not only a strong offense, but a strong defense and good goaltending- putting together the pieces for a championship-winning team. These are beast teams. Therefore we will call them beasts.
We can do this by creating another variable we will call GD for Goal Differential, where GD = GF-GA. So the question here is: what percentage of teams with high goal differentials (GF-GA) go on to win the Stanley Cup?

#add a column for computing the Goal Differential
teams <- teams %>%
  mutate(GD = (GF-GA))
#Order by teams that have the highest GD
beasts <- teams %>%
  arrange(desc(GD))
kable(head(beasts, 5))

Showing Up When it Matters

We still want to improve our chances of winning the cup. They say it’s not about how good a team’s record is, rather it’s the teams that heat up towards the end of the year that are the most dangerous. We saw this in full effect last year as the Pitsburgh Penguins, who had a coaching change in the middle of the season, turned things around dramatically and went on a Stanley Cup winning run as basically a 4 seed in the Eastern Conference.

There’s another dataset from Kaggle under the same pro hockey database that breaks down team stats by month. I want to plot out monthly win percentages for Stanley Cup winnning teams to see if they usually end with an upward trend. The dataset is called TeamSplits.csv.

splits <- read.csv("TeamSplits.csv")
teamsSplits <- full_join(splits, teams, by = c("year", "tmID"))
teamSplitsWinners <- teamsSplits %>%
  filter(playoff == 'SC')
nrow(teamSplitsWinners)
## [1] 97

Now we want to get the win percentages by month for every team and plot them if the teams ended on an upswing. Then by doing that, we’ll know how many (if any) of the Stanley Cup winners ended on a hot streak.
NOTE: The way I’m calculating an upswing ending to the year is if FebPct <= MarPct <= AprPct || FebPct <= MarPct. I make this a two option thing because some teams either didn’t play regular season games in April (back in the old days) or play a rather negligible amount of games in April (like less than 5) so I don’t think it really matters too much if their record is still good (maybe like 2-2) if their Feb-March improvement is stellar.

#Select the desired columns
tswbymonth <- teamSplitsWinners %>%
  select(year, tmID, OctW, OctL, NovW, NovL, DecW, DecL, JanW, JanL, FebW, FebL, MarW, MarL, AprW, AprL) %>%
#calculate win percentages by month
  mutate(OctPct = 100*OctW/(OctW+OctL), NovPct = 100*NovW/(NovW+NovL), DecPct =  100*DecW/(DecW+DecL), JanPct = 100*JanW/(JanW+JanL), FebPct = 100*FebW/(FebW+FebL), MarPct = 100*MarW/(MarW+MarL), AprPct = 100*AprW/(AprW+AprL))

#Fill the 'Hot' Column with NA's
tswbymonth <- tswbymonth %>%
  mutate(Hot = NA)

#Iterate over the column and assign values
for(i in 1:nrow(tswbymonth)){
  Feb <- tswbymonth[i, ]$FebPct
  Mar <- tswbymonth[i, ]$MarPct
  Apr <- tswbymonth[i, ]$AprPct
  if((Feb <= Mar && Mar <= Apr) || (Feb <= Mar)){
    tswbymonth[i, ]$Hot <- T
  } else{
    tswbymonth[i, ]$Hot <- F
  }
}


We need to gather the data into a better format, group by year and team, and arrange in descending order by year. We’re going to call it tswbymonthP where the P is for Plottable, because in the format it’s in now it can’t be plotted nicely.

tswbymonthP <- gather(tswbymonth, "Month", "Percent", 17:23) %>%

So now we have data frames for every Stanley Cup winner from 1970-on. I ran into a problem whenever I tried to plot their win percentages though… Let’s see how the win percentages for Boston in 1970 looked over the course of the year.

ggplot(bos1970, aes(x=Month, y=Percent, group=1)) + geom_point(color = 'orange', size = 4) + geom_line()


Notice how the months are ordered on the x-axis- alphabetically. That’s no good. I want them ordered chronologically. I found this question on StackOverflow that helped me very much. Turns out getting ggplot to keep the order of your axes is harder than it should be…

plts <- list()
hotTeams <- list()
for(p in 1:length(puck)){
  dat <- puck[[p]]
  #StackO said to transform your column to character
  dat$Month <- as.character(dat$Month)
  #then reorder it as factor in the unique levels it's in
  dat$Month <- factor(dat$Month, levels = unique(dat$Month))
  #append ggplot statement to list plts
  plts[[p]] <- ggplot(dat, aes(x=Month, y=Percent, group=1)) + geom_point(color='orange', size=4) + geom_line()
}


So what I’ve basically made is a list of plots that I can call and it will plot for me. How did Boston ACTUALLY do that year? 

plts[[1]]


This graph looks good! So Boston didn’t necessarily end “hot”. And believe it or not, I found as a side effect that you can store ggplot statements in a list and call those plots by referencing a position in the list. In theory, it makes sense that you should be able to do that, but when R actually allowed me to do it I thought it was very cool.

Machine Learning in Hockey

That 8% was still a tough one to swallow… but I have one more trick up my sleeve… Machine Learning!. Let’s see if any basic decision trees can give me any tips on what a team has to do to maximize their chance of winning the cup.
First we need to transform teamsSplits back to how it was.

teamsSplits <- full_join(splits, teams, by = c("year", "tmID"))

Now we can continue on with the Machine Learning.

mod1 <- party::ctree(playoff == 'SC' ~ Pts + GD + PIM + PPG, data = teamsSplits)
plot(mod1, type = "simple")


Ok, so with a goal differential greater than 124, you’ve got a 55.6% chance of winning the cup. Great, THANKS party- you drastically improved something I already tried to explore. Well let’s see what the log_likelihood is for this model. We want a log_likelihood of as close to 0 as possible.

teamsSplits %>%
  mutate(probability = as.numeric(predict(mod1)),
         likelihood = 
           ifelse(playoff == 'SC', 
                  probability, 
                  1 - probability)) %>%
  summarise(log_likelihood = sum(log(likelihood)))
##   log_likelihood
## 1      -254.8984


Ok, I think this is decent. In the Machine Learning Activity we did in class, we were getting values in the negative 6 and 4 thousands, so this model must be decently confident. Though, I do believe we are working with significantly less data. I digress…

Let’s see if we can improve our model by adding some better things and taking some things away.

mod2 <- party::ctree(playoff == 'SC' ~ GD + PIM + MarW + rank, data = teamsSplits) #add March Wins and rank, get rid of Pts and PPG
plot(mod2, type = "simple")


Ok so no real change in our success rate. Is this a better model? 

teamsSplits %>%
  mutate(probability = as.numeric(predict(mod2)),
         likelihood = 
           ifelse(playoff == 'SC', 
                  probability, 
                  1 - probability)) %>%
  summarise(log_likelihood = sum(log(likelihood)))
##   log_likelihood
## 1      -251.5907


Barely. Let’s keep trying out some variable combinations.

mod3 <- party::ctree(playoff == 'SC' ~ Pts + MarW + rank + GD + PIM + PPG, data = teamsSplits)
plot(mod3, type = "simple")


Is this a better model?

teamsSplits %>%
  mutate(probability = as.numeric(predict(mod3)),
         likelihood = 
           ifelse(playoff == 'SC', 
                  probability, 
                  1 - probability)) %>%
  summarise(log_likelihood = sum(log(likelihood)))
##   log_likelihood
## 1      -262.8831


Nope, it’s worse. So I’m gonna call it here and say that our best model is indeed mod2. I’m sure it can be improved, but this has been a tiresome Exploratory Data Analysis, so I’m going to wrap it up.
